1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,161
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodassa

2
00:00:17,141 --> 00:00:33,603
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:33,624 --> 00:00:42,976
So we've been through the opening of this Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta, which if you remember rightly means turning the wheel of the law.

4
00:00:43,637 --> 00:00:46,220
It's the first discourse that the Buddha gave.

5
00:00:46,841 --> 00:01:14,975
or at least it states the basic platform of his teaching which were the four noble truths and we went through the first noble truth which explains the truth of suffering the second one is the cause of suffering and the third one is that it's the cessation of suffering the end of suffering so the fourth one is the noble path leading to the end of suffering

6
00:01:15,748 --> 00:01:28,903
And that noble path is right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, and right mindfulness, and right concentration.

7
00:01:28,963 --> 00:01:42,280
The normal way that this is expressed is through these three divisions, sila, samādhi, paññā, which means the ethical life, ethics, the meditation,

8
00:01:43,507 --> 00:02:12,300
meditation as a practice but also as something that subsists through our lives and wisdom sort of turns it around really because the path comes wisdom first then right effort and then the meditation so we'll do it the way it comes here anyway this right view, this right understanding it refers specifically to these Four Noble Truths

9
00:02:12,584 --> 00:02:15,367
and especially to the three characteristics.

10
00:02:16,590 --> 00:02:27,247
So it's actually seeing impermanence, becoming more and more aware of the impermanent nature of our existence, seeing the role of desire.

11
00:02:28,128 --> 00:02:29,811
Remember this is the wrong desire.

12
00:02:30,032 --> 00:02:33,336
We're not talking about the desire to meditate, anything like that.

13
00:02:33,396 --> 00:02:37,203
We're talking about desire which is seeking happiness in the sensual world.

14
00:02:38,806 --> 00:02:40,228
Seeking happiness in the sensual world.

15
00:02:42,165 --> 00:02:45,471
You have to remember that the Buddha ethicized everything.

16
00:02:45,991 --> 00:02:49,296
From the Buddha's point of view, everything was an ethical problem.

17
00:02:49,717 --> 00:02:51,259
See, these days we don't see it like that.

18
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:56,448
We see from psychotherapy, we see it as a medical problem, a mental problem.

19
00:02:56,467 --> 00:02:59,233
From the Buddha's point of view, everything is an ethical problem.

20
00:02:59,252 --> 00:03:03,819
And the reason is that right at the beginning, somewhere, we made this mistake.

21
00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:05,823
And the mistake is one of identity.

22
00:03:06,644 --> 00:03:10,349
This identity means that we consider ourselves to be human beings.

23
00:03:10,769 --> 00:03:13,012
This is a really very deep and profound mistake.

24
00:03:15,375 --> 00:03:20,981
Thinking ourselves to be human beings, we're now trying to seek happiness in the human world, which is the sensual world.

25
00:03:22,223 --> 00:03:29,712
Now, as soon as we seek happiness in the sensual world, we begin to accumulate, become acquisitive, and that turns to greed.

26
00:03:30,554 --> 00:03:35,199
When you gain something and hold something, somebody else wants it, so you've got to protect it.

27
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:38,784
So you're into aversion, you're into hatred, you're into conflict.

28
00:03:39,524 --> 00:03:42,627
And if the other person's too big, you run for it, you interfere.

29
00:03:43,429 --> 00:03:48,754
So you've got these three fundamental positions.

30
00:03:48,775 --> 00:03:53,961
You've got one of acquisitiveness, collecting, greed, because that makes you feel safe.

31
00:03:55,582 --> 00:03:57,945
The more money in the bank you've got, the more safe you feel.

32
00:03:59,127 --> 00:04:00,348
And aversion and fear.

33
00:04:00,368 --> 00:04:05,776
So there's your basic stance in life from the point of view of this wrong understanding.

34
00:04:06,276 --> 00:04:07,016
And therefore...

35
00:04:07,334 --> 00:04:12,060
All our problems arise from that, you see.

36
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:17,627
On the positive side, of course, we have compassion, you know, love, sympathetic, joy and peace.

37
00:04:17,648 --> 00:04:19,870
And, of course, that takes us away from our problems.

38
00:04:19,990 --> 00:04:22,593
Then we form a very different relationship to life.

39
00:04:23,495 --> 00:04:31,605
So, from the Buddha's point of view, all our suffering is based on this wrong understanding which produces an ethical situation.

40
00:04:32,427 --> 00:04:36,312
See, and that's why what we do

41
00:04:36,899 --> 00:05:06,146
is what determines our future so this right view that's what it means it's beginning to understand that and the other part of right view is to understand that the world we live in is the world that we create there's no objective world that's a myth I came up with

42
00:05:06,447 --> 00:05:08,809
our 18th century enlightenment and science.

43
00:05:09,470 --> 00:05:12,673
But the world that we experience doesn't have any objectivity.

44
00:05:12,872 --> 00:05:14,295
It's completely created by us.

45
00:05:14,915 --> 00:05:19,920
And we create an illusion that we can see the world as it is.

46
00:05:21,862 --> 00:05:30,550
But these days neurobiology is proving without any shadow of a doubt that we can only see the world the way we see it, within our own heads.

47
00:05:32,512 --> 00:05:35,694
So once you realize that, then you realize that

48
00:05:36,045 --> 00:06:06,019
whatever information is coming in through the senses what we do with it is completely up to us so if we're living in an awful world that's our problem it's not anybody else's problem and then we have to find a way out so that's what we generally mean by this right view now this right view when it becomes a right view not a wrong view it's no good having it up there in the sky as a sort of understanding

49
00:06:06,336 --> 00:06:36,158
it has to penetrate and the first penetration is into the heart and that manifests as an attitude and that's the second part you see so it's no good saying oh yes everything's interconnected and interdependence and then go around shooting people I mean he's got to descend into the heart as some form of interconnectedness which means compassion right so that from the heart's point of view interconnectedness is love interconnectedness is compassion sympathetic joy see

50
00:06:36,795 --> 00:07:06,567
if it doesn't it just remains this cold philosophical idea that everybody's connected now once it's moved into the heart again it's a waste of time it has to move out into the body once it moves into the body it begins to express itself so that's where you get right speech right action and right livelihood now this right livelihood isn't strictly necessary because in a sense it's included in action

51
00:07:06,884 --> 00:07:36,250
but the Buddha puts it there and you've only got to consider what qualities your livelihood develops what qualities livelihood develops in a person so I mean just think of the qualities of a policeman suspicious and a teacher see a teacher always asks questions they can answer they never ask one they can't answer there's all sorts of see so your profession what you actually do

52
00:07:36,483 --> 00:07:40,567
has a direct effect upon your character, your personality.

53
00:07:40,608 --> 00:07:46,375
Especially when you think that you spend probably the best energy of your life in it.

54
00:07:47,838 --> 00:07:49,319
Eight hours a day, whatever it is.

55
00:07:49,899 --> 00:07:52,923
So you can see it has a direct effect.

56
00:07:52,944 --> 00:07:54,586
So he puts it as quite separate, you see.

57
00:07:55,146 --> 00:08:01,154
And perhaps another reason is that it's through livelihood that we act in the world, you see.

58
00:08:01,875 --> 00:08:02,997
And that's our karma.

59
00:08:05,372 --> 00:08:35,008
so that's how we go from right understanding into a right attitude and out through the world into right speech right action right livelihood now the last three are to do with our mental state state of awareness and that's right effort right mindfulness and right concentration this right effort of course is this right mindfulness you've got to catch you see in our meditation we

60
00:08:35,225 --> 00:09:01,840
we have this objective position within us where we're trying to investigate the psychophysical organism and try to find out what we're doing wrong why we're so miserable see now that's not the that's not what you take into daily life see into daily life this the you're not trying to watch yourself see when you're doing a job when you're doing we'll say when you're washing the pot you're not trying to watch yourself wash the pots

61
00:09:02,225 --> 00:09:05,688
If you do that, you just break a few and get very angry with yourself.

62
00:09:06,049 --> 00:09:08,692
You can't watch yourself adding up bills.

63
00:09:09,634 --> 00:09:10,375
You get them all wrong.

64
00:09:10,875 --> 00:09:14,239
So you're not trying to take that objective position.

65
00:09:14,480 --> 00:09:16,642
You're trying to absorb into your action.

66
00:09:17,243 --> 00:09:21,187
And to absorb into your action in a way that isn't going to cause you suffering.

67
00:09:21,648 --> 00:09:23,791
So there are two qualities that you have to develop.

68
00:09:24,071 --> 00:09:25,332
This sense of attention.

69
00:09:25,994 --> 00:09:26,995
So that's your samadhi.

70
00:09:27,014 --> 00:09:29,298
That's your concentration.

71
00:09:29,317 --> 00:09:30,859
It's got to have the right attitude.

72
00:09:30,879 --> 00:09:32,181
So it's coming from care.

73
00:09:32,971 --> 00:10:01,154
right the job itself you're doing has to be wholesome in itself and you put yourself into it now as you're doing something say gardening even a hobby like gardening should we say you might become aware of yourself you know as of a general self-awareness so that arises naturally we're not trying to develop that then you put your attention into the work now if you've gone into that work with attention and care

74
00:10:01,995 --> 00:10:10,227
and you absorb into that work, you lose a sense of self, there's nobody there doing it, and you lose a sense of time.

75
00:10:11,168 --> 00:10:13,993
So self and time are the same thing.

76
00:10:14,033 --> 00:10:22,725
Time, existence, self, they're all there as an objectivity which takes us out of the moment.

77
00:10:24,086 --> 00:10:31,597
Now you can't help it, coming out of the moment and becoming self-aware, but you're not developing that, you're trying to develop this absorption, putting yourself right into what you're doing.

78
00:10:32,067 --> 00:10:32,267
See?

79
00:10:33,568 --> 00:10:39,759
Now, when you absorb into what you're doing, you are developing the qualities that that job is demanding.

80
00:10:41,181 --> 00:10:49,052
So, if you go into it with greed, if you go into it with indulgence, you come out with a dependency.

81
00:10:51,596 --> 00:10:51,697
Yeah?

82
00:10:51,717 --> 00:10:55,764
And if you go into it with a pure heart, you come out with a pure heart.

83
00:10:56,424 --> 00:10:56,504
See?

84
00:10:57,750 --> 00:11:03,839
So that's why it's so important that when you start a job, you just stop for a moment, get your attitude right.

85
00:11:04,078 --> 00:11:04,299
See?

86
00:11:04,399 --> 00:11:05,181
Right attitude.

87
00:11:05,500 --> 00:11:06,863
Your understanding right.

88
00:11:07,423 --> 00:11:09,466
And then you give yourself to the job.

89
00:11:09,485 --> 00:11:11,328
And that's mindfulness in ordinary daily life.

90
00:11:13,412 --> 00:11:25,868
And the purpose of the sitting meditation is to establish that sense of awareness, a sense of mindfulness within ourselves, so that in a sense, throughout daily life,

91
00:11:26,219 --> 00:11:28,442
there's also a connection with ourselves.

92
00:11:28,883 --> 00:11:35,833
So that we see, for instance, if you're talking to somebody, you're there with the first rising of irritation, you know, just before you hit them.

93
00:11:35,854 --> 00:11:42,283
You hit them, you can feel the little movement in the heart, you see, because you're there, it doesn't move, you see, it just stays there, you see.

94
00:11:42,904 --> 00:11:50,255
But often, because we're not aware of it, it's growing up here around the back, you see, and then suddenly you find yourself shouting your head off.

95
00:11:50,275 --> 00:11:50,495
See?

96
00:11:50,897 --> 00:11:53,660
So, to be like that, you've also got to be very relaxed.

97
00:11:54,096 --> 00:11:59,583
See, there's lots of, it's dreadful trying to develop this stuff.

98
00:12:01,667 --> 00:12:20,711
So you can see this eightfold path is actually to be taken both, the last bit, the right concentration, right effort, right mindfulness, is both, goes to one side in terms of a process of self-investigation, which we call vipassana, insight and all that,

99
00:12:21,113 --> 00:12:29,162
and the other side is this mindfulness that we take into right speech, right action, right livelihood.

100
00:12:29,182 --> 00:12:30,403
Now it all turns on itself.

101
00:12:30,744 --> 00:12:42,798
Now you can see that from the Buddha's point of view, being a Buddha, one who knows, his own liberation came through in an investigation.

102
00:12:43,818 --> 00:12:46,763
So that's why right view is at the top, the right investigation.

103
00:12:47,864 --> 00:12:50,326
But there are definite signs in the scriptures

